===Etymology===
{{calque|en|frm||n'y avoir ryme ne raison}} ({{w|Eustache Deschamps}}), attributed to the poet {{w|Edmund Spenser}} in a conversation with Queen Elizabeth I.<ref>{{w|Edmund_Spenser#Rhyme_and_reason|''Rhyme and reason''}}</ref> {{rfv-etym|en|contradicting sources}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en|En-au-rhyme or reason.ogg|Audio (AU)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-}}

# {{lb|en|idiomatic|no rhyme or reason|without rhyme or reason}} {{l|en|[[logic|Logic]]; [[common sense]].}}
#: {{ux|en|Prices vary considerably from one town to another with no apparent '''rhyme or reason'''.}}
#: {{ux|en|He would often fly into an unexpected rage without '''rhyme or reason'''.}}

====Usage notes====
* Almost always used in a negative form, particularly with {{m|en|no}} and, adverbially, {{m|en|without}}. May also occur as ''rhyme nor reason'', e.g. after ''neither''.

